===Etymology 2===
{{etymid|ja|festival}}
<div style="float:right;">
{{wp|ja:[[お盆|お盆 (Obon)]]}}
[[File:Mukaebi_20120731.jpg|thumb|250px|{{lang|ja|盆}}: [[Obon]]. Lighting the welcome [[beacon]]s in [[w:Numazu,_Shizuoka|Numazu]], [[w:Shizuoka_Prefecture|Shizuoka Prefecture]].]]
{{wp|Bon Festival}}
</div>
{{ja-kanjitab|ぼん|yomi=goon}}

Short for {{m|ja|盂蘭盆|tr=Urabon}} or {{m|ja|盂蘭盆会|tr=Urabon'e}}, from {{der|ja|ltc|盂蘭盆|tr=hju lan bwon|sort=ほん'}} or {{m|ltc|盂蘭盆會|tr=hju lan bwon hwaj<sup>H</sup>}} (compare modern {{cog|cmn|盂蘭盆|tr=yúlánpén}} or {{zh-l|盂蘭盆會|tr=yúlánpénhuì}}), a transcription of {{der|ja|pi|sort=ほん'|ullumpana||raising, helping}}, [[present participle]] of {{cog|pi|-}} verb {{m|pi|ullumpati||to raise up, to help}}.

A number of Japanese dictionaries state that this term derives from {{cog|sa|उल्लम्बन}}, purportedly meaning “hanging upside-down” in reference to the souls of the dead being tortured in hell by being strung up by their feet.<ref name="KDJ">{{R:Kokugo Dai Jiten}}</ref><ref name="DJR">{{R:Daijirin}}</ref><ref name="DJS">{{R:Daijisen}}</ref><ref>{{R:Shinmeikai5}}</ref> However, the {{cog|sa|-}} word was sparsely, if at all, attested ({{zh-ref|Ashikaga, 1951}}); in addition, it would be the [[present participle]] of verb {{m|sa|उल्लम्ब्||to hang|pos=intransitive}}, with no inherent “upside-down” meaning.<ref>[http://spokensanskrit.org/index.php?tran_input=ullamb ''ullamb''-related entries at SpokenSanskrit.org website]</ref><ref>[http://sanskritdictionary.com/ullamb/42749/1 ''ullamb'' entry at Sanskrit Dictionary website]</ref>

Moreover, neither the purported meaning of “hanging upside-down” nor the verifiable meaning of “hanging” match the semantics very well, given that the ''urabon'' ceremonies are about helping the dead, closer in meaning to the “helping” sense of the {{cog|pi|-}} verb.<ref>[https://dsalsrv04.uchicago.edu/cgi-bin/app/pali_query.py?qs=Ullumpana&searchhws=yes ''ulllumpana'' entry at The Pali Text Society's Pali-English Dictionary website]</ref> This suggests that explanations of the dead hanging upside-down in hell are more likely to be [[folk etymologies]] based on a mistaken connection to the {{cog|sa|-}} verb, rather than a more direct semantic link to the {{cog|pi|-}}. Alternatively, {{w|Junjirō Takakusu}} (''apud'' {{zh-ref|Ashikaga, 1951}}) propounded that the origin was in fact {{cog|pi||ullumbana}}, a colloquial corruption of {{cog|pi|ullumpana||raising up; saving; helping}}, and that the etymology was mistakenly attributed to Sanskrit.

